# git SSH commit-signing trusted signers (gpg.ssh.allowedSignersFile, #19).
#
# Non-secret: these are PUBLIC keys, safe to commit. This file lets
# `git log --show-signature` verify locally without contacting GitHub.
#
# Format (one signer per line):  <principal> <keytype> <base64-key>
#   e.g.  williams.r.drew@gmail.com ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAA...
#
# The signing key is generated on first boot (host-key-style, see home.nix), so its
# public half is not known until then. FILL THIS IN during the #24 bootstrap ritual:
#   1. cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519_signing.pub
#   2. paste it below as `williams.r.drew@gmail.com <that line>`
#   3. upload the SAME public half to GitHub as a *Signing* key
#   4. commit this file
#
# Until filled, signatures verify as unverified locally — expected, not a bug.
williams.r.drew@gmail.com ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIN2ATR0DHwQz48bQTqUO4KFySdXaBcbjssm3seEGsoJf drewos commit signing key
